					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.4) </p></aside>
							Find the following determinant by expanding along the first row and the second column.
							<me> \begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} </me>
						</statement>

						 <hint xml:id="hint-section-4-2-problem-2-hint-1">
						For a <m>3\times3 </m> matrix,<m> A </m>, expanding along the <m>i</m>th row,
						<me>\det(A) = a_{i1}cof(A)_{i1}+a_{i2}cof(A)_{i2}+a_{i3}cof(A)_{i3}</me>
						</hint> 
						<hint xml:id = "hint-section-4-2-problem-2-hint-2">
						For a <m>3\times3 </m> matrix, <m>A</m>, expanding along the <m>j</m>th column,
						<me>\det(A) = a_{1j}cof(A)_{1j}+a_{2j}cof(A)_{2j}+a_{3j}cof(A)_{3j}</me>
						</hint>
						<answer>
						The determinant of the matrix is 6.
						</answer> 
						 <solution>
						 For a <m>3\times3 </m> matrix, expanding along the <m>1</m>st row,
						<me> cof(A)_{11} = (-1)^{1+1}\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} =-2 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{12} = (-1)^{1+2}\begin{vmatrix} 2 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix}=(-1)(-4)=4 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{13} = (-1)^{1+3}\begin{vmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix}=(-1)(0)=0 </me>
						<me>\det(A) = a_{11}cof(A)_{11}+a_{12}cof(A)_{12}+a_{13}cof(A)_{13}=(1)(-2) + (2)(4)+ (1)(0)=6 </me>
						For a <m>3\times3 </m> matrix, expanding along the <m>2</m>nd column,
						<me> cof(A)_{12} = (-1)^{1+2}\begin{vmatrix} 2 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} =(-1)(-4)=4 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{22} = (-1)^{2+2}\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix}=(-1)=-1 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{32} = (-1)^{3+2}\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 3 \end{vmatrix}=(-1)(1)=-1 </me>
						<me>\det(A) = a_{12}cof(A)_{12}+a_{22}cof(A)_{22}+a_{32}cof(A)_{32}=(2)(4) + (1)(-1)+ (1)(-1)=6 </me>
						The determinant of the matrix is 6.
						</solution> 		
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.5) </p></aside>
							Find the following determinant by expanding along the first column and the third row.
							<me> \begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} </me>
						</statement>

						<hint>
						See <xref ref="hint-section-4-2-problem-2-hint-2"/> for the definition of a matrix determinant found by expanding along the jth column.
						</hint>
						<hint>
						See <xref ref="hint-section-4-2-problem-2-hint-1"/> for the definition of a matrix determinant found by expanding along the ith row.
						</hint> 
						<answer>
						The determinant of the matrix is -6.
						</answer> 
						<solution>
						 For a <m>3\times3 </m> matrix, expanding along the <m>1</m>st column,
						<me> cof(A)_{11} = (-1)^{1+1}\begin{vmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} =-1 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{21} = (-1)^{2+1}\begin{vmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix}=(-1)(1)=-1 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{31} = (-1)^{3+1}\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{vmatrix}=-2 </me>
						<me>\det(A) = a_{11}cof(A)_{11}+a_{21}cof(A)_{21}+a_{31}cof(A)_{31}=(1)(-1) + (1)(-1)+ (2)(-2)=-6 </me>
						For a <m>3\times3 </m> matrix, expanding along the <m>3</m>rd row,
						<me> cof(A)_{31} = (-1)^{3+1}\begin{vmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} =-2 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{32} = (-1)^{3+2}\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix}=0 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{33} = (-1)^{3+3}\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{vmatrix}=-2</me>
						<me>\det(A) = a_{12}cof(A)_{12}+a_{22}cof(A)_{22}+a_{32}cof(A)_{32}=(2)(-2) + (1)(0)+ (1)(-2)=-6 </me>
						The determinant of the matrix is -6.

						</solution> 
						
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.7) </p></aside>
							Compute the determinant by cofactor expansion.  Pick the easiest row or column to use.
							<me> \begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2\\  2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} </me>
						</statement>

						<hint>
						For a <m>4\times 4 </m> matrix,<m> A </m>, expanding along the <m>i</m>th row,
						<me>\det(A) = a_{i1}cof(A)_{i1}+a_{i2}cof(A)_{i2}+a_{i3}cof(A)_{i3}+a_{i4}cof(A)_{i4}</me>
						</hint> 
						<answer>
						The determinant of the matrix is -4.
						</answer>
						 <solution>
						 We choose the third row because this choice gives us the most amount of zeros, which means we have less cofactors to compute.
						 For a <m>4\times 4 </m> matrix,<m> A </m>, expanding along the <m>3</m>rd row,
						<me>\det(A) = a_{31}cof(A)_{31}+a_{32}cof(A)_{32}+a_{33}cof(A)_{33}+a_{34}cof(A)_{34}</me>
						<me>\det(A) = (0)cof(A)_{31}+(0)cof(A)_{32}+(0)cof(A)_{33}+(2)cof(A)_{34}</me>
						<me> cof(A)_{34} = (-1)^{3+4}\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{vmatrix} </me>
						Let <m> B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} </m>. To find the determinant of <m> B </m> we will
						expand along the first row, since it has the most amount of zeros.  
						<me> det(B) = b_{11}cof(B)_{11} + b_{12}cof(B)_{12} + b_{13}cof(B)_{13} </me>
						<me> det(B) = (1)cof(B)_{11} + (0)cof(B)_{12} + (0)cof(B)_{13} = (1)(-1)^{1+1}\begin{vmatrix}1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{vmatrix} = 2 </me>
						<me> cof(A)_{34} = -2 </me> 
						<md>
						<mrow> \det(A) \amp = (0)cof(A)_{31}+(0)cof(A)_{32}+(0)cof(A)_{33}+(2)cof(A)_{34} </mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = (2)(-2) </mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = -4 </mrow> </md>
						The determinant of the matrix is -4.
						</solution> 
						
					</exercise></p>
